import pandas as pd
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

Background on preprocessing for this dataset, from the website:
https://ifcs.boku.ac.at/repository/data/spike_sorting/

Each row represents a set of 96 features characterizing the spatiotemporal electric field. The features were produced by an automatic spike detection algorithm taking the first 3 principal components from some filtered waveforms coming from the recording. Waveforms were recorded using a probe inserted into the brain consisting of 32 different channels. Features 3k+1,3k+2,3k+3 correspond to the 3 PCs of Channel k.

# First apply PCA on the dataset
ncomp = 2
pca = PCA(n_components = 2, whiten=True)
pca.fit(X)

Z = pca.transform(X)
In [6]:
# Pairplot of the projection on the principal components
plt.figure()
sns.pairplot(data=pd.DataFrame(Z, columns=['PC1', 'PC2']));

<Figure size 432x288 with 0 Axes>
In [7]:
# Apply Kmeans on the first two components
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters = 2, n_init=100, init ='random')
kmeans.fit(Z) # apply Kmeans using the first two components of Z
labels = kmeans.labels_
Z2 = pd.concat([pd.DataFrame(Z,columns=['PC1','PC2']),pd.DataFrame(labels, columns=['Cluster label'])], axis=1)
In [8]:

Remember that input 3k+1:3k+3 corresponds to features of the time series of channel k. Cluster 0 therefore corresponds to a neuron activating the channels 1-14 (large values for inputs 1-44), and the cluster 1 corresponds to a neuron activating the channels 24-29 (large values for inputs 72-89)
